{{Infobox journal | title = Third World Quarterly | cover = | editor = Shahid Qadir | discipline = [[Area studies]], [[development studies]] | abbreviation = | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | country = | frequency = Monthly | history = 1979–present | impact = 1.434 | impact-year = 2014 | website = http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/CTWQ | link1 = http://www.tandfonline.com/loi/ctwq20 | link1-name = Online archives | ISSN = 0143-6597 | eISSN = 1360-2241 | OCLC = 615555785 | LCCN = 80640150 | CODEN = | JSTOR = 01436597 }} '''''Third World Quarterly''''' is a [[peer-reviewed]] [[academic journal]] published by [[Routledge]], established in 1979. {{As of|2017}}, its [[editor-in-chief]] is Shahid Qadir. It was published eight times per year until 2011, when publication increased to ten times per year.<ref>{{cite web | title = Third World Quarterly | url = http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/CTWQ | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] |accessdate= 29 April 2011}}</ref> It is now published monthly.<ref>{{cite web | title = Third World Quarterly | url = http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/CTWQ | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] |accessdate= 21 February 2015 }}</ref>
According to the ''[[Journal Citation Reports]]'', the journal had an [[impact factor]] of 1.451 in 2014, ranking it 35th out of 55 journals in the category "Planning and Development".<ref name="WoS">{{cite book|title=2014 [[Journal Citation Reports]]|last=|first=|publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]]|year=2014|isbn=|edition=Social Sciences|series=[[Web of Science]]|location=|pages=|chapter=Journals Ranked by Impact: Planning and Development}}</ref>
==Controversy== In September 2017, the journal attracted controversy after it published an article entitled "The Case for Colonialism" by political scientist [[Bruce Gilley]]. This was described by Portia Roelofs and Max Gallien of the [[London School of Economics]] as "a travesty, the academic equivalent of a Trump tweet, clickbait with footnotes."
On 19 September 2017, a large number of the journal's [[editorial board]] resigned in protest, citing a flawed peer review process for the colonialism submission and inaccurate statements from the editor-in-chief, Shahid Qadir.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Thomas, Rosamma|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/uk/journals-editorial-board-resigns-over-colonialism-essay/articleshow/60754617.cms|title=Journal's editorial board resigns over colonialism essay |work=The Times of India|date=19 September 2017|access-date=19 September 2017}}</ref> In all, 15 of the 34 members of the international editorial board were signatories to the resignation letter. A petition at [[Change.org]] to retract the piece had more than 10,000 supporters.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/09/19/controversy-over-paper-favor-colonialism-sparks-calls-retraction|title=Controversy over a paper in favor of colonialism sparks calls for retraction|last=Flaherty|first=Colleen|date=19 September 2017|work=[[Inside Higher Education]]|access-date=19 September 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chronicle.com/blogs/ticker/editorial-board-of-third-world-quarterly-resigns/120188|title=Editorial Board of ‘Third World Quarterly’ Resigns|last=Zamudio-Suaréz|first=Fernanda|date=20 September 2017|work=The Chronicle of Higher Education|access-date=23 September 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/simon-dawes-co-signatories/open-letter-to-third-world-quarterly-on-publication-of-case-for-coloniali|title=Open letter to Third World Quarterly on the publication of 'The case for colonialism'|date=20 September 2017|work=openDemocracy|access-date=23 September 2017|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref>
