A massive fireball was recorded above Siberia, near [[Yekaterinburg]], on November 14, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://themoscowtimes.com/articles/russian-officials-left-puzzled-after-fireball-explodes-above-sverdlovsk-video-41513 |title=Russian officials left puzzled after fireball explodes above Sverdlovsk |author=Anna Dolgov |publisher=The Moscow Times |date=November 19, 2014 |accessdate=2016-10-15}}</ref> The explosion apparently happened near the city of [[Rezh]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.rt.com/news/206691-sverdlovsk-urals-sky-flash |title=Chelyabinsk meteor #2? Massive flash over Russia’s Urals stuns locals & scientists |author= |publisher=Russia Today |date=November 18, 2014 |accessdate=2016-10-15}}</ref>

Various explanations have been raised. The Russian Ministry for Emergency Situations said it was an on ground explosion,{{cn|date=May 2018}} but the Siberian Times, a local newspaper, noted that "the light was not accompanied by any sound".<ref name="siberiantimes001">{{Cite web |url=http://siberiantimes.com/other/others/news/n0027-new-evidence-that-fire-in-the-sky-was-caused-by-military/ |title=New evidence that fire in the sky was caused by military |author= |publisher=The Siberian Times |date=November 23, 2014 |accessdate=2016-10-15}}</ref> Regarding the meteoroid hypothesis, the Siberian Times also noted that "a local observatory indicated nothing fell from the sky on the day of the flash".<ref name="siberiantimes001"/> Another hypothesis that was raised is the [[high-altitude nuclear explosion]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://assopyrophor.org/2015/08/16/the-flash-light-in-siberia-nov-14-2014-a-nuclear-test-in-space-le-flash-en-siberie-du-14112014-un-test-nucleaire-dans-lespace/ |title=The flash light in Siberia, November 14, 2014: a nuclear test in space |author= |publisher=Association Pyrophor |date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=2016-10-15}}</ref>{{better source|date=May 2018}}

